[1
Date: Wed, 14 Jul 1999 08:42:28 +0100
From: Ernest Gould <EAG@wpo.nerc.ac.uk>

With reference to the discussion on tick feeding habits and forest
temperatures, we have three comments to make:
1. In our experience (in English woods/forests) tick feeding activity is
optimal at about 20C and decreases significantly when the ambient
temperature rises above about 22C to 23C.
2. Ticks do not climb trees. If a tick inadvertantly landed on a tree when
it dropped off a bird, it would almost certainly be engorged (otherwise it
would not normally drop off the animal) and therefore be unlikely to feed
again immediately. Interrrupted feeding is very rare with ticks and is
likely to lead to damage to the tick, thus impairing its
feeding capacity.
3. In our experience (remember this is England and may be different from
other countries), the habitat determines which instar will feed on humans.
When conditions are optimal, ie high humidity and 20deg.C and under the
shade of the trees, nymphs or larvae would be the most common predators on
humans. Adult ticks attach to humans more rarely when [the latter are
collecting ticks in the forests using blanket-dragging techniques,
--
