[Most of this information is correct but Omsk hemorrhagic fever (OHF) is not
a subtype of Russian Spring-Summer encephalitis (RSSE).
Let's start at the beginning: First, tick-borne encephalitis (TBE) is the
name for a
clinical diagnosis. When one considers that the bacterium _Borrelia
burgdorferi_, the etiologic agent of Lyme disease can cause encephalitis,
and therefore "tick-borne encephalitis", it becomes apparent that it is best
to speak of the specific etiologic agent causing an illness.
When speaking of TBE, either the term "TBE virus" should not be used or the
names for various agents that cause than syndrome should be dropped; one or
the other. The problem is that some people use both, as it suits them or
out of ignorance.
Among the family Flaviviridae, genus _Flavivirus_, are a number of
tick-borne viruses that can cause human illness. Without going into awful
detail, let me say only that there are not huge differences between Central
European encephalitis (CEE) virus and RSSE virus but there are some
differences. Franz Heinz and his associates in Vienna have done elegant
work on the molecular characteristics of many of these viruses, as have
Ernie Gould (writer of Part [1 above) and his associates. Numerous
publications have appeared in the literature and they are recommended to
those who want to know more.
However, as always, shoddy classification leads to poor communication. Omsk
hemorrhagic fever, the disease, is caused by OHF virus, related to but quite
distinct from RSSE virus. Moreover, OHF and RSSE (the diseases) are not at
all similar to each other, except that they are caused by related viruses.
Differences in antigenic, molecular, and ecological characteristics of these
two viruses are clear-cut.
Bottom lines:
CEEV causes TBE
RSSEV causes TBE
CEEV and RSSEV are very closely related to each other
TBE is a euphemism for any of a number of diseases but usually is meant to
indicate infection with CEEV
OHFV is something else, but not altogether something else
The etiology of "TBE" in Moscow likely is CEEV; the etiology of "TBE" in
Vladivostok likely is RSSEV.
The Austrian "TBE vaccine" is prepared with the Neudorfl strain of CEEV.
It is a good vaccine for at-risk humans and protects mice against RSSEV
infection as well as against CEEV.
Let's move on. String cut, unless we receive additional information on
Russian cases of TBE. - Mod.CHC
...........................chc/jw
